\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Sheaf condition for $\Omega_{X/S}$]
  \label{thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf_isSheaf}
  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
  The relative cotangent presheaf is a sheaf in the Zariski topology on $X$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
  The proof proceeds in three steps: reduction of the sheaf-of-modules condition to a sheaf-of-abelian-groups condition restricted to the affine basis; verification of that condition on basic opens via the localisation compatibility of K\"ahler differentials; and descent from the basis to all opens.

  \emph{Reduction to the affine basis of abelian-group sections.} The sheaf condition for a presheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules coincides with the sheaf condition for its underlying presheaf of abelian groups, because the forgetful functor $\mathrm{ModuleCat}\,R \to \mathrm{AddCommGrp}$ creates and reflects the relevant equalizer-based limits. The Lean entry point for this reduction is \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.isSheaf\_iff\_isSheaf\_comp} composed with the forgetful functor $\mathrm{ModuleCat}\,R \to \mathrm{AddCommGrp}$. Furthermore, the affine opens of $X$ form a basis of the Zariski topology (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.isBasis\_affineOpens}), so for a presheaf valued in a category with the necessary products and equalizers the sheaf condition on the affine basis suffices to imply the sheaf condition on every open cover, by basis-to-opens descent.

  \emph{Affine basis case via localisation compatibility.} Fix affine opens $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$ and a standard basic open $D(f) \subseteq V$ for $f \in B$. The presheaf assigns to $D(f)$ the K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A}$. Mathlib's \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.isLocalizedModule\_map} provides, as an \texttt{IsLocalizedModule} instance for the multiplicative set $\{f^n\}_{n \geq 0}$, the canonical isomorphism
  \[
    \Omega_{B[1/f]/A} \;\cong\; \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f];
  \]
  the tensor-product form is also packaged as \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.tensorKaehlerEquiv}. This is the content of Stacks Tag~01UM (and Hartshorne~II.8, Proposition~8.2A): K\"ahler differentials commute with localisation. The localisation compatibility identifies the affine-basis presheaf with the structure of a quasi-coherent $\struct{V}$-module on $V = \Spec B$: on each basic-open cover $V = \bigcup_i D(f_i)$ (equivalently $(f_1, \dots, f_n) = (1)$ in $B$), the equalizer
  \[
    \Omega_{B/A} \;\longrightarrow\; \prod_i \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f_i] \;\rightrightarrows\; \prod_{i,j} \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f_i f_j]
  \]
  is exact in $B$-modules, since tensoring a $B$-module with the standard sheaf condition for $\struct{V}$ over the cover $\{D(f_i)\}$ preserves exactness when the cover is finite (or, equivalently, the $B$-module $\Omega_{B/A}$ admits a quasi-coherent extension to $\Spec B$ and quasi-coherent sheaves on an affine scheme satisfy the affine sheaf condition).

  \emph{Basis-to-opens descent.} Once the sheaf condition has been verified on the affine basis, it extends to all open covers by the unique-gluing criterion \texttt{TopCat.Presheaf.IsSheaf.isSheafUniqueGluing}, applied to the affine basis \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.isBasis\_affineOpens}. Concretely, given any open cover $\{U_\alpha\}$ of an open $W \subseteq X$, refine each $U_\alpha$ to a cover by affine opens contained in $W$; the basis-restricted sheaf condition supplies a unique gluing on the refinement, and the unique-gluing axiom on the original cover follows from the refinement's universality.

  We note explicitly that the alternative route through \texttt{SheafOfModules.IsQuasicoherent} is not viable: that abstraction packages a sheaf of modules together with its quasi-coherent local description, but it requires the underlying presheaf to already be a sheaf — which is precisely the statement we are proving.
\end{proof}

